Korean 2 (Continuing Introductory Korean) is the second part of first year Korean. Instructor’s consent is required to take this course. The objective of the course is to equip students with communicative skills in speaking, listening, reading, and writing at the basic level in Korean. The textbook is designed for college students in the US. Students will learn beginning level Korean in everyday life contexts. In the classroom, students are encouraged to use only Korean.
Cho, Y-M., Lee, H. S., Schulz, C., Sohn, H-M., Sohn, S-O. 2010. Integrated Korean: Beginning 2. 3rd edition. Honolulu: University of Hawaii Press.
Park, M. 2010. Integrated Korean Workbook: Beginning 2. 3rd edition. Honolulu: Univ of Hawaii Press.
Textbook and Workbook Audio Files: downloadable from Resources on Sakai and also at (Audio Services - ‘Beginning Two’)

• You are expected to attend all classes and be punctual. For attendance and participation, students will be given a daily grade, which ranges from 0 to 3. This daily grade will be based on attendance and punctuality, preparation, and performance during class.

• Arriving late and leaving early with no valid reason will be a major part of your daily participation grade. If you have a circumstance that makes your arrival on time difficult, you should inform me. A special circumstance can be communicated after class, and frequent instances of late arrival (previous class is located too far away) should be communicated at the beginning of the semester.

• If you arrive after attendance is checked, it is your responsibility to contact the instructor and request a change from “absence” to “late arrival.” Missing more than 15 minutes of a class three times is considered one absence.

Students are not allowed to leave their cell phone or computer out during class unless they are required for class activities (e.g., Kahoot). Any material that is not related to Korean class (including another course’s materials) is not allowed to be on the desk or in your hand. Never do your Korean homework in class. Each violation will reduce your participation grade.
No hats during exam; if necessary, please wear it backwards.

Every four absences will result in an automatic lowering of one third of a letter grade (e.g., if a student’s grade is B+, four absences lower it to a B, and eight absences to a B-). Twelve or more absences will result in an F, regardless of the student’s performance in the class.
Absences are excused only with valid documentation (e.g., a doctor’s note, an email from a professor or coach). Only the dates specified on the note will be excused.
Challenges can be discussed and handled on case-by-case basis under the current pandemic situation, so please do not hesitate to consult the instructor for any concern or question.

If you receive notification from Hamilton Health Box that you are required to isolate/quarantine, please let me know as soon as possible that you are unable to attend class in person. If you are well enough to participate, I will have Zoom up and running in the classroom so that you can join us remotely. If you are not well enough to participate, we will find other ways to support you.
In general, if you feel ill and cannot attend the class, you should contact the student health service or Timely MD to receive a doctor’s note. Absences can be excused only with a doctor’s note.
Course Website & Email: For any updates related to the course schedule and assignments, check the course website on Sakai and also check your email on a regular basis.
Conversation Classes: Students are required to attend weekly conversation class with the language resident.
The language resident will grade your performance in her class.
Unexcused absences will result in a reduction of participation points.
Please fill out the Conversation Class Google Form by Thursday, Jan. 20th at noon.
Pre-class Lesson Activities: Students must complete assigned lesson activities on Sakai (organized by week) before EACH class.
You should do the quiz only after completing the pre-class lesson on Sakai.
You will receive your grade immediately upon completing the quiz, and you can retake the quiz as many times as you want.
Your answers become final at 9:00AM before class each day. At that time, the correct answers are released.
Quizzes will be available from Thursday before the assigned week onward. You can finish one week’s quizzes in advance during the weekend if you want.
Once the due time has passed, you cannot make up for missed quizzes.
Quizzes are set up for auto submission, which means that even if you do not press the “submit” button, your existing answers will be submitted automatically at the due time.
Workbook Homework: For each chapter, students will submit two workbook assignments.
The list of mandatory exercises and the due dates are on page 4 of this syllabus.
It is recommended that students work on all the exercise questions of each chapter. The answer keys for the non-mandatory ones will be posted on Sakai.
Homework assignments must be stapled and ready to be submitted at the beginning of class on the dates they are due.

Make sure to complete all sections; some questions continue on the next page (e.g., L16, WR G p167). When the homework grade is low for being incomplete, students are allowed to complete the missing questions and resubmit their homework for grade improvement only once per semester. In that case, the student should resubmit within one week of the original due date.

Students will earn 90% of the total grade for homework that is up to three hours late, 80% for homework that is one day late, and after that, 10% additional deduction per day; for homework that is one week late, no credit will be given. Exceptions can be made only with valid documentation. Even with a valid documentation, if the student does not submit homework until one week after the original due date, no credit will be given. Exceptional cases should be discussed with the instructor in advance.

If a student is absent on the date when the homework is due without valid documentation, even if the homework is submitted the next day, it will receive 80% of the total grade. If a student does not come to class on the date when the homework is due, the student should 1) make a PDF copy of the homework and email me the file (pdf only) before the due time, 2) leave the homework in my mailbox outside of my office before the due time or 3) have a fellow student bring it to class.
Exams: There will be three mid-course exams and one final exam.
The Common Final Exam time for all sections of Korean 1: TBA
Students are not allowed to do extra work near the end of the semester for the purpose of improving their grade.
Vocabulary Quizzes: Each lesson has two vocabulary quizzes. Do not be late for class on the vocab quiz day.
The grade of the lowest vocabulary quiz will be dropped at the end of the semester.
Compositions: Students are required to write two short compositions.

The instructor will provide feedback with comments (i.e., mistakes in grammar (G), spelling (S), spacing (|) etc.) on a first draft. Students will then re-submit a revised version with the original with instructor’s remarks attached.
Only the revised, final composition will be graded. Students will lose points from the perfect score of 10 based on remaining mistakes.

Please format your composition as follows: 12 lines (till the end of the page, meaning not 12 sentences), double-spaced, 12-size font, and 1-inch margins on all sides. A first draft or a final submission that does not follow the specified format will lose points.
The same late submission policy as for homework will be applied to compositions.
Students can use a dictionary to look up specific new words but are not allowed to use google translate or to receive help from native speakers.
Write about what you did during your winter break.
Write a letter (for an example, look at the narration from lesson 14).
Speaking Tests: There will be three speaking tests.
1) & 2) Dialogue: Make a conversation with a partner.
• Tests are given in the conversation class.
• Example format for Test 2 (a telephone conversation) can be found in Lesson 13.
3) Final Interview: One-on-one interview with the instructor in week 16. Interview questions will be provided prior to the interview date.
Oral Skit: In groups of 2-4, students will prepare a short skit and either film it or perform it in front of class.
• Manuscripts of the skit will be turned in beforehand for instructor feedback.
• Each of the participants should have at least 10 substantial lines of talk, excluding greetings, exclamations and short utterances.

• Students must 1) use language appropriate for the class (i.e., do not overuse vocabulary that fellow classmates do not know); 2) memorize their lines thoroughly (i.e., do not read from scripts); and if recorded, 3) make sure that the audio is clear (e.g., do not film where noise levels are high).

Language Table: Students are required to attend the language table at least 4 times during the semester (week 2 through week 15). Not attending 4 times per semester will result in a deduction of participation points. Attending the Korean language table at Oldenborg at Pomona does not count towards the requirement but is recommended.
Wednesdays 12:00 at Collins Dining Hall, CMC Thursday 12:00 at Oldenborg Center, Pomona
Make-up Policy: No make-up quizzes and exams will be allowed without valid documentation.

Missing a vocab quiz due to late arrival without a valid reason will follow the same policy; the missed quiz will be counted as the student’s lowest vocab quiz which will be dropped. Students are required to make up the missed quiz or exam within one week of the missed date. Special circumstances should be discussed with the instructor in advance.
Mask Policy: Masks are required in Korean 2.
• Podcasts and YouTube: ‘Talk to me in Korean’, ‘Let’s speak Korean’, etc.
Note: Korean 2 is a letter grade only class.

Your experience in this class is important to me. If you have already established accommodations with Accessibility Services at your campus, please communicate your approved accommodations to me at your earliest convenience so we can discuss your needs in this course. If you have not yet established accommodations through Accessibility Services, but have a temporary health condition or permanent disability (conditions include but are not limited to: mental health, attention-related, learning, vision, hearing, physical or health), you are encouraged to contact Accessibility Services.
The college’s statement of academic integrity and academic integrity violation procedures are found at the college’s website. Excerpts are shown below.

“Cheating on assignments or examinations of any kind (homework, quizzes, midterms, finals, etc.) includes copying another student’s answers, exchanging information, using notes or books unless expressly permitted to do so by the instructor, having forbidden devices or materials in the testing environment, or gaining access to examinations prior to the actual taking of such examinations.” “Supplying false or forged documents to a college official” is also an act of violation.
Sharing Course Materials Outside the Class

Sharing any course materials outside the class is strictly prohibited. Course materials are the intellectual property of the instructor who creates them. Thank you for respecting the enormous amount of work it takes to develop high-quality course materials by not sharing them outside the class.
